Name: n-Tetracosane
Description: Tetracosane is a straight-chain alkane containing 24 carbon atoms. It has a role as a plant metabolite and a volatile oil component.

fish_seafood_concentrations.References: (1) Al-Hassan JM et al; Bull Environ Contam Toxicol 65: 646-53 (2000) (2) Al-Hassan JM et al; Bull Environ Contam Toxicol 66: 646-52 (2001)
fish_seafood_concentrations.Value: Barnacle samples collected from five locations in the Arabian Gulf had concentrations of tetracosane ranging from not detected to 860 ng/g(1). Catfish samples collected from seven locations in the Arabian Gulf had concentrations of tetracosane ranging from <0.1 to 113 ng/g(2).

sediment_soil_concentrations.References: (1) Hori T et al; Bull Environ Contam Toxicol 83: 455-461 (2009)
sediment_soil_concentrations.Value: SEDIMENTS: Tetracosane was detected in sediment samples from from 14 sites along the Shinano River in Japan, from Nov 2005 to April 2006, at concentrations ranging from 3.0 to 38 ng/g(1).

sediment_soil_concentrations.References: (1) Rushdi AI et al; Arch Environ Contam Toxicol 49: 457-470 (2005)
sediment_soil_concentrations.Value: SOIL: During winter 2002 soil and sand samples, from six locations in the Riyadh metropolitan area of Saudi Arabia, were examined for extractable organic matter; tetracosane was detected at relative concentrations between 0.24 to 0.81% (of total extractable organic matter) at five of six locations(1).
